%S A396561 1,1,2,1,1,3,1,1,2,2,1,1,4,1,1,3,1,2,4,1,2,1,1,1,1,1,2,1,1,5,1,1,5,3,
%T A396561 2,1,1,6,1,1,3,1,1,1,2,2,1,2,1,1,4,1,1,7,1,1,3,2,1,2,2,3,1,1,6,1,1,1,
%U A396561 2,1,1,1,1,1,2,8,1,2,5,1,1,2,1,3,3,2,1
%N A396561 a(n) = A008479(A280864(n)).
%C A396561 Let s = A280864 and let rad = A007947.
%C A396561 Let R_k be the sorted sequence {k*m : rad(m) | k}, with k > 1 a squarefree number and let R_1 = {1}. Then this sequence is the position of s(n) in R_rad(s(n)). (See Selcoe's comment in A280864.)
%C A396561 Consider s(n), s(n+j), with j >= 1 the smallest such that rad(s(n)) = rad(s(n+j)) = k is true. Then a(n+j) = a(n)+1. (Note, j always exceeds 1 as a consequence of the definition of A280864).
%C A396561 a(n) = 2 and s(n) with more than 1 distinct prime factor implies s(n) in A366825.
%C A396561 a(A280774(n)+1) = 1 for A280774(n) != 10 at least for A280774(n) <= 26403.
%C A396561 a(A280774(n)+2) = 1 at least for A280774(n) = 3..26403.
%H A396561 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A396561/b396561.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A396561 a(n) >= 1.
%F A396561 a(n) = 1 for squarefree s(n).
%F A396561 For s(n) = p^m, prime p and m > 0 (s(n) in A246655), a(n) = m.
%e A396561 Terms s(n) appear in A280864 in the order in which they appear in R_rad(s(n)). For instance, those s(n) whose squarefree kernel is 6 appear in the order that they appear in A033845 = {6, 12, 18, 24, 36, 48, 54, ...}. These numbers appear in A280864(i) for i = {5, 9, 16, 19, 33, 38, 54, ...}, respectively. Thus in this sequence, we see a(5) = 1, a(9) = 2, a(16) = 3, a(19) = 4, etc.
%e A396561 .
%e A396561 Let T(j,k) denote the k-th term in block j of A280864, with k = 1..A283832(j).
%e A396561 Table showing the k-th term in block j of A280864 (top) and the corresponding term in this sequence below it, for j = 1..12. Thus, T(3,2) = s(5) = 6 = A033845(a(5)) = 1, T(4,3) = s(9) = 12 = A033845(a(9)) = 2, etc.
